    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_7c26b0cf",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 74,
      "author": {
        "id": 1976
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:53:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Consider initializing the Kafka client/producer once for all requests",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_c22235a2",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 74,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Agree with Jonathan\u0027s POST above. Initialization logic should be done in the constructor following the Resource Initialization is Acquisition principle in OO design. In other words create objects in their fully constructed state. Don\u0027t do partial object creation. That would take the code below\n\n               if not self.client or not self.producer:\n                    self._init_kafka()\n\nand it would get moved into the constructor as just\n\nself._init_kafka() and be done once and never need to be looked at again.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_9e0b4923",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 94,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This method should be moved into a resource class called something like \"MetricsResource\" with a method called \"on_post\".\n\nAs we add other resource, like Measurements and Alarms, they should all be in their own files/classes.\n\nThe KafkaDIspatcher should purely be about sending messages to Kafka and initialized one somewhere and passed into a resource class for MetricsResource and everything else.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_deadd132",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 94,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:31:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "imagine you have many other methods to handle different http requests at\ndifferent endpoint. Really not like having to use the method name to do that.\nthat was whole point of having a subclass.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_9e0b4923",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_a21d3164",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 94,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That is exactly what I imagine. A class called MetricResource with several methods in it corresponding to each HTTP VERB that is supported. One method for POST and one for GET, ... The use of classes to model resources really helps out with grouping.\n\nIndependent of modeling resources as classes putting on_post_metrics in side a class called KafkaDispatcher is clearly poor OO design. \n\nThink about in the future when I want to have RabbitMQDispatcher or MockDispatcher.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_7e06a51d",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 101,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In my performance analysis this sort of loop to copy the data over was slower than just reading it all in at once.\n\nJust wondering why this was added. For example, was it performance related or some other reason.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_9e6fc9fb",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 101,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:31:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "the problem is that you do not know how much to read. performance wise,\nthere is no difference.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_7e06a51d",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_e2f8197e",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 101,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "From the Falcon API documentation for stream\n\nEither a file-like object with a read() method that takes an optional size argument and returns a block of bytes, or an iterable object, representing response content, and yielding blocks as byte strings. Falcon will use wsgi.file_wrapper, if provided by the WSGI server, in order to efficiently serve file-like objects.\n\nWhat that says is that the size parameter is optional. I read that to mean if it isn\u0027t supplied the amount of data to read will be computed. That is what I wrote in my implementation which I tested and it worked.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_bc0018ac",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 103,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "If you wrote this as \n\nif not msg:\n    res.status \u003d ?\n    return\n\nyou wouldn\u0027t have to indent everything else in this method.\n\nI\u0027m not exactly sure what the Java implementation does in this case, but I would be happy to test it out.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_7e414562",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 103,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:31:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "in python, I believe return in the middle of a method is a bad practice. Some\nmay like that style. I do not.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_bc0018ac",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_c2007568",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 103,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Cite me a reference on that. Here is one for you to read. http://stackoverflow.com/questions/36707/should-a-function-have-only-one-return-statement\n\nAll these indented blocks make it much harder to read the code and for something like input validation in which it is very clear what is being done and tested and that you don\u0027t want to continue unless input validation has been succesful it is much nicer to have at the top.\n\nIf this was a return statement in the middle of several nested blocks of code, that would be different, and I would agree doing something like that should be avoided.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_fe729548",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 106,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:03:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "There needs to be some input validation on the message prior to doing any further processing on it.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_fe2b7592",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 106,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:31:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "we talked about this. adding your own middle ware to do that.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_fe729548",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_e26d7933",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 106,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I understand that we talked about it, that doesn\u0027t mean I think that it is a good idea. \n\nAnyway, I\u0027m kinda wondering how that would work and what would be implemented in the end using the middle-ware approach.\n\nAnother way that seems much more straight-forward is to just have a check for\n\nif is_input_validation:\n    do_input_validation()\n\nrather than implementing as middle-ware. The code is nice and localized in that case.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_fd9a7b12",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 106,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T20:20:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Roland, I would like you to read wsgi tutorial. Which will help you to\nunderstand this. Using a code here will not allow you to use configuration\nto take away these validations. I will write a small middleware to demostrate\nhow this is done. Actually there are already two middlewares in the code.\nYou can use it in the wsgi pipeline to do things. This way, use it or not is\na configuration choice, not a code choice.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_e26d7933",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_9c24340e",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 109,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Do you really want to do manual retries like this?\n\nI think it would be OK to not retry at all and return a 500 or 503 error rather than retry at all.\n\nUnfortunately, I didn\u0027t see an option for retrying in the Python Kafka Client, but all this retry looping would be repeated everywhere if we did this.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_a10b8c22",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 109,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:31:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I would think so. fail faster is fine as well. Trying to be nice.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_9c24340e",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_c2a15547",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 109,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So, I think retry logic is desirable.\n\nMy preference would be then to have an interface for talking to queues that has a method in it called something like \"send_messages\"\n\nThe Kafka implementation of that would implement the retry logic:\n\nclass KafkaDispatcher(object):\n    self.producer \u003d ...\n\n    def send_messages(...):\n        while True:\n            self.producer.send_messages(...)\n            ...\n\nThis way we don\u0027t end-up repeating the same exact code and the same indented code block in every single method that handles a http request.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_5c3e4cdb",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 113,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Note, \"compact\" isn\u0027t supported in the rest of the Monasca implementation.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_e1103450",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 113,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:31:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "just an option. if we really want to be fast, we should not parse here. \nwe discussed this before as well.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_5c3e4cdb",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_428d65d2",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 113,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It isn\u0027t an option that works today anywhere in the rest of the Monasca system.\n\nWhy are we adding options and code that doesn\u0027t work?\n\nIf/when we get to doing something like this we can add it and completely implement it in the rest of the system. I\u0027m not accepting any partially implemented options and code.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_3c3988f2",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 120,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The problem with this loop is that for each metric it tries to convert to a string and send the metric, but if it fails an exception is caught down below in the ValueError exception block, which could occur partially through the list.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_e13e74b7",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 120,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:31:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "not sure there is anything you can do though. if we receive a lot of message\nin one request and monasca requires send one by one. I thought this is what\nhp does. I would rather not to support this.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_3c3988f2",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_624b4987",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 120,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Sure, there are ways of coding for this.\n\nClearly what is implemented will return a success to the client half-way through the list if they ended up with bad data in there.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_fd68bbf6",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 120,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T20:20:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "not really. the problem is that if you have many messages in one request.\nthey are all good ones in terms of the format, remember the validation\nmiddleware I was talking about. The problem is that if kafka goes down or this service goes down after first few messages are sent successfully. then you have a partial message sent, other part not, you can fail the entire request, but still you may end up with duplicate data in the system. Again, I argue that using the distributed unique id will ease this problem.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_624b4987",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_b51d5f11",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 120,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-13T13:04:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We\u0027ll have to discuss. I\u0027m not sure how the distributed unique ID fits in.\n\nMy preference is to fail the entire message or process it completely. If you fail the entire message, at least the client knows it was not processed and can try again, hopefully with a smaller message. \n\nThat is a good point about how we currently handle the Kafka messages though. The entire http request is not processed atomically in our current system as we add each metric to the queue separately. If Kafka goes down partially through, then we\u0027ll end-up in a partially processed state. \n\nThat would argue for passing the metrics in as arrays, which is what your \"compact\" option is for. So, I agree that this would be a good option to add. However, since the rest of the Monasca system doesn\u0027t support it yet, and we still will need the tenant ID, region, and creation_time, we still can\u0027t pass the original http request body exactly through the system.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_3e009d00",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The message that is sent here does not match what is currently used in Monasca. In other words, this code doesn\u0027t work.\n\nWhat is required right now is something the following:\n\n{\"metric\":{\"name\":\"disk_space_utilization_perc\",\"dimensions\":{\"service\":\"monitoring\",\"device\":\"v-csdb-3\",\"hostname\":\"mini-mon\"},\"timestamp\":1410459284,\"value\":87.36112721917534},\"meta\":{\"tenantId\":\"3c1f6223f44d42c0b88623e75ed3c996\",\"region\":\"useast\"},\"creation_time\":1410459285}",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_e16594e1",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T21:31:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "it did not care. it is a json and it will send. validate the message in your\nvalidator. stop the flow before it reaches this point.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_3e009d00",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_025c3d4a",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T17:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This doesn\u0027t work with the rest of the Monasca system as it is currently defined. \n\nClearly this code was never tested with the rest of the Monasca system.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_201f765c",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 2860
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T20:20:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "it posts the messages onto the queue. With your own validator in the pipeline,\nvalid message gets here and will be posted onto the queue. This code\nsupports sending message in bulk and one by one. I am not sure why it\nwon\u0027t work with rest of the Monasca system.",
      "parentUuid": "fa98f980_025c3d4a",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_35640fb8",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-13T13:04:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It won\u0027t work with the rest of the current Monasca system as it is currently implemented. \n\nIn this porting effort I think we should first be maintaining a fully functional system as in the current components, whether they are Java or Python, all continue to work. We can then come back and re-visit message formats and see if there are any improvements that could or should be made.\n\nThe current message format required by the rest of the Monasca pipeline is a JSON message with a few parts in it.\n\n{\n    \"metric\": {The metric as a JSON object},\n    \"meta\": {\n        \"tenantId\": \"the tenant ID acquired via authentication with Keystone\",\n        \"region\": \"the region that the metric was submitted under\",\n    },\n    \"creation_time\": the time when the API received the metric as UNIX time\n}\n\nThat is what the rest of the current Monasca system expects.\n\nAs far as I recall in my performance analysis there wasn\u0027t a significant performance difference when just passing the metric through as compared to what is listed above.\n\nCurrently, we need the tenant ID, region and creation_time in the format above.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_1873d04e",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 123,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-12T18:25:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "One other point related to this is that we need extra information, such as the tenantId, region and creation_time included in the message that is published to Kafka. The full message is listed above. The persister and other down-stream components use the tenant ID as this is a multi-tenant system and the database schemas require this information too.",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa98f980_dcc23c52",
        "filename": "monasca/dispatcher/kafka_queue.py",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 124,
      "author": {
        "id": 2419
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-09-11T20:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is a lot of debug logging messages which could really fill up the log file and make it very difficult to read when trying to debug.\n\nMaybe this log message and the one above should be moved to LOG.trace, but I\u0027m wondering if that should be reported?",
      "revId": "abaf9e2b2c41a167b79388aa3c4f482f81ae7887",
      "serverId": "4a232e18-c5a9-48ee-94c0-e04e7cca6543",
      "unresolved": false
